value.value: A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm affecting the spinal cord.  Representative examples include lymphoma, melanoma, and sarcoma.
An infection that is caused by Trichomonas.

A form of schizophrenia characterized by delusions (of persecution or grandeur or jealousy); symptoms may include anger and anxiety and aloofness and doubts about gender identity; unlike other types of schizophrenia the patients are usually presentable and (if delusions are not acted on) may function in an apparently normal manner.
The uterus has descended below the level of the hymen and protrudes through the opening of the vagina.
A non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder that affects the nasopharynx.  Representative examples include nasopharyngitis, angiofibroma, and carcinoma.
A displacement of a part (especially a bone) from its normal position.
A heart defect which is inborn or present at birth.
A heart or vascular abnormality which is inborn or present at birth.
A malignant neoplasm that affects the pineal region.
An infection that is caused by Gonococcus.
A partial or complete loss of hearing in one or both ears. It is classified as conductive, sensory, or central.

A rare, highly aggressive carcinoma that arises from the salivary gland, predominantly the parotid gland.  It is characterized by the presence of large pleomorphic malignant cells with or without neuroendocrine differentiation. Patients usually present with a rapidly growing mass.

A rare carcinoma that arises from the salivary glands, most often the parotid gland.  It is characterized by the presence of an undifferentiated carcinomatous component associated with a prominent reactive lymphoplasmacytic infiltrate.
A rare, aggressive carcinoma that arises from the salivary glands.  It is characterized by the presence of a squamous and a glandular epithelial component.

A rare, benign, encapsulated epithelial tumor composed of cells that form solid, variably shaped islands and cysts, both showing focal sebaceous differentiation. The mean age of patients is reported to be 58 years, and most tumors occur in the parotid gland. There is a male predominance. Most patients are asymptomatic.
A carotid body paraganglioma that metastasizes to other anatomic sites.
A term that includes all non-neoplastic vascular disorders.
A non-neoplastic disorder that affects the heart and/or the pericardium.  Representative examples include congestive heart disease, endocarditis, and constrictive pericarditis.

A non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder that affects the thorax and/or the organs of the thoracic cavity.  Representative examples include pleural infection, mediastinitis, thymoma, mediastinal lymphoma, and pleural mesothelioma.

A non-neoplastic disorder that affects the thorax and/or the organs of the thoracic cavity.  Representative examples include pleural infection, mediastinitis, pneumonia, and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.
A non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder that affects the sternum.
A non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder that affects the structures of the chest wall.  Representative examples include infection, chest wall lipoma, and chest wall lymphoma.

A non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder that affects the structures of the axilla.  Representative examples include axillary lymphadenitis, axillary lipoma, and metastatic carcinoma to the axillary lymph nodes.
A non-neoplastic disorder that affects the structures of the axilla.  Representative examples include axillary lymphadenitis and axillary abscess.

label.value: Metastatic Malignant Neoplasm in the Axilla

value.value: A malignant neoplasm that has spread to the structures of the axilla from another anatomic site.

A benign or malignant neoplasm that affects the structures of the axilla.  Representative examples include axillary lipoma, axillary lymph node lymphoma, and metastatic carcinoma to the axillary lymph nodes.
A malignant neoplasm affecting the endocrine glands.  Representative examples include thyroid gland carcinoma, parathyroid gland carcinoma, pituitary gland carcinoma, and adrenal cortex carcinoma.
A neoplasm that arises from the axilla and is characterized by the absence of atypical or malignant cytological and architectural features, and absence of invasive features or metastatic potential.
A non-neoplastic disorder that affects the sternum.
A non-neoplastic disorder that affects the structures of the chest wall.
A non-neoplastic disorder that affects the trachea.  Representative examples include tracheitis, tracheal agenesis, and tracheal atresia.
A rare, fatal congenital malformation in which the trachea is severely underdeveloped.
A non-neoplastic disorder that affects the respiratory system.  Representative examples include pneumonia, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, pulmonary failure, tracheitis, and tracheal agenesis.

label.value: Stage IIIB Lung Small Cell Carcinoma with Pleural Effusion AJCC v7

value.value: Stage IIIB small cell lung carcinoma that has spread to the pleural fluid.

label.value: Stage IIIB Lung Small Cell Carcinoma without Pleural Effusion AJCC v7

value.value: Stage IIIB small cell lung carcinoma that has not spread to the pleural fluid.

label.value: Stage 0 Lung Large Cell Carcinoma AJCC v6 and v7

value.value: Stage 0 includes: Tis, N0, M0.  Tis: Carcinoma in situ.  N0: No regional lymph node metastasis.  M0: No distant metastasis. (AJCC 6th and 7th eds.)

label.value: Metastasizing Pleomorphic Adenoma of the Salivary Gland

value.value: A very rare pleomorphic adenoma of the salivary glands that metastasizes inexplicably, despite the benign histopathologic features.  The most common sites of metastasis are bone, lung, and head and neck.
A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm affecting the tissues of the thorax.
Any disorder of the joints.
Arthropathy that is not permanent.
Any arthropathy that is caused by trauma.
A syndrome caused by thiamine deficiency. It usually occurs in alcoholics and is characterized by confusion, ataxia, and ophthalmoplegia.
